'''Deutoplasm''' refers to the food particles stored in the [[cytoplasm]] of an [[ovum]] or a cell, as distinguished from [[protoplasm]], the [[yolk]] substance. Generally, the deutoplasm accumulates about the [[cell nucleus|nucleus]] and is heavier than the surrounding cytoplasm. In [[chicken egg]]s, the cytoplasm and deutoplasm are separate.<ref>{{cite book |last= Bailey|first= Frederick|date= 1911|title= Text-book of Embryology|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=VG4aAAAAYAAJ&dq=deutoplasm+is+the+food+in+cytoplasm&source=gbs_navlinks_s|publisher= W.Wood and Company|page= 12}}</ref>

