A '''musical argument''' is a means of creating [[tension (music)|tension]] through the relation of [[emotional expression|expressive content]] and [[musical form]]:
{{quote|Traditional [[dialectic|dialectal]]{{efn|The purpose of the dialectic method of reasoning is resolution of disagreement through rational discussion between opposing viewpoints.}}
 music is [[representation (arts)|representational]]: the musical form relates to an expressive content and is a means of creating a growing tension; this is what is usually called the musical argument.|[[Wim Mertens]] (1999)<ref>Mertens, Wim (1999). ''American Minimal Music: La Monte Young, Terry Riley, Steve Reich, Philip Glass'', reprinted edition (London: Kahn & Averill), p.88. {{ISBN|1871082005}}. Quoted in LaBelle, Brandon (2006). ''Background Noise'' (London and New York: Continuum), p.7. {{ISBN|9780826418449}}.</ref>}}
Experimental musics may use [[process music|process]] or [[indeterminacy (music)|indeterminacy]] rather than argument.<ref>LaBelle (2006), p.7.</ref>

The musical argument may be characterized as the primary flow and current idea being presented in a piece:
{{quote|The very definition of musical argument is something that keeps going, and you uncover new details and new combinations. A musical argument is not the same as a [[disagreement|verbal argument]]. A [[debate|verbal argument]] implies that there's {{sic}} two sides; a musical argument makes the two sides one thing, like [[counterpoint]]. A [[fugue]] is like that; a [[Fugue#Double (triple, quadruple) fugue|double fugue]], at least, takes two different [[theme (music)|ideas]] and shows you how they relate, and it shows you how they're the same thing.|[[Phil Lesh]] (1982)<ref>Gans, David (2002). ''Conversations With The Dead'', p.166. {{ISBN|9780306810992}}.</ref>}}
Thus one may hear of a musical argument being interrupted, extended, or [[repetition (music)|repeated]].{{or-inline|date=February 2017}}

